Study of the human fecal matter pollution of northern Sydney beaches by measuring enterococci bacterial populations.

Project 2

Zeke Yu 490401066 | Muhammad Abbas Junejo 470348996 | Ayodele Olufowose 490577305 | Bangshuo Zhu 490477027

University of Sydney | MATH1005 | Nov 2019


1 Executive Summary

The aim of this report was to study the changes in the populations of Enterococci bacteria in different beaches around sydney. This was done by looking at the number of colony forming units of the bacteria in the different beaches over the course of 2018. The main discoveries were that most of the beaches studied were well below dangerous levels of 40 cfu/100mL, and that there was a relationship between the seasons and the amount cfu levels of the beach. However, beaches like Dee Why beach and the Bilarong reserve amongst others showed high levels of contamination, rising to unsafe levels in more than one month. It was also found that the variation in levels between winter and summer was not due to seasonal changes in temperature however, but rather was due to seasonal rainfall.

Summary:

The data was obtained from the NSW Government Office for Environment and Heritage, a governmental body responsible for the care and protection of the natural environment amongst other things. The data is valid because they are set up to monitor natural resources such as bodies of water, and therefore have the equipment ant professionals to collect accurate samples and results. Some possible issues we found with the database are: First, the data samples were collected every six days throughout the season. The article by Rozin and Belkin in 2001 states that the bacteria lose their ability to form colonies as soon as they are out of the body, and therefore the amounts measured every six days may not be representative for the other days. Secondly, we do not know how many samples were collected per beach, and therefore dont know if the samples are representative of the whole beach or only specific locations on the beach. Also, the NSW Government Office for Environment and Heritage use the population of enterococci as a measure of human fecal matter contamination, however, according to the paper by Boehm and Sassoubre in 2014, there may be other sources of the bacteria including plants and on rare occasions beach soil. Finally, the article by Rozin and Belkin states that major factors that affects colony growth include sunlight and temperature, both of which vary throughout the day. Because we dont know when in the day the samples were collected, we cannot say how these factors may have affected our dataset.

Each row of the dataset represents information regarding the concentration of enterococci of different beaches on different dates. Each column represents the independent or dependent variables of the data.

2.2.2 Conclusion

There are varying cfu levels for beaches throughout the three months. Following is the analysis for each month:

December: Many beaches have shown quite low cfu levels, the lowest amongst them being Bilgola Beach, Bungan Beach, North Steyne Beach, Whale Beach and Palm Beach. However, there were some which were nearly crossing the supposed borderline for safe cfu level (40 cfu/100mL). These include Bilarong Reserve (Narrabeen Lagoon), Birdwood Park (Narrabeen Lagoon), Dee Why Beach, Long Reef Beach and North Narrabeen Beach.

January:

It was quite unclear from the plot with many outliers, which ones were the safest. However, after making another graph with the outliers removed, it became clearer as to which beaches had the highest levels of cfu. They included Bilarong Reserve (Narrabeen Lagoon), Dee Why Beach, Freshwater Beach, North Steyne Beach and South Curl Curl Beach. The safest included Avalon Beach, Bungan Beach, Long Reef Beach, Mona Vale Beach, Palm Beach, South Steyne Beach and Whale Beach.

February:

In February, only Bilarong Reserve (Narrabeen Lagoon) seemed to have increased cfu levels. While on the other hand, many of the beaches showed very low cfu levels excluding some beaches on certain days. For example, Bilgola Beach, Dee Why Beach, Long Reef Beach and Turimetta Beach.

Beaches to avoid: Bilarong Reserve (Narrabeen Lagoon) and Dee Why Beach.

Safest beaches: Bungan Beach, Palm Beach, Avalon Beach, Whale Beach and Bilgola Beaches.

2.3 Research Question 2

Do Enterococci bacteria thrive more in summer than in winter?

2.3.1 Working

Winter <- data[data$Month=="June" | data$Month=="July" | data$Month=="August",]
plot(Winter$BeachId,Winter$Enterococci..cfu.100ml., xlab = "BeachId", ylab = "Enterococci cfu. 100mL", main = "Winter")

Summer <- data[data$Month=="December" | data$Month=="January" | data$Month=="February",]
plot(Summer$BeachId,Summer$Enterococci..cfu.100ml., xlab = "BeachId", ylab = "Enterococci cfu. 100mL", main = "Summer")

Mean of Enterococci concentration during Winter (m1):

## [1] 31.52922

Mean of Enterococci concentration during Summer (m2):

seasondiff <- m1 - m2

Standard deviation of concentration during Winter (sd1):

sd1 <- sd(Winter$Enterococci..cfu.100ml.)
sd1

Standard deviation of concentration during Summer (sd2):

sd2 <- sd(Summer$Enterococci..cfu.100ml.)

n1 <- length(Winter$Enterococci..cfu.100ml.)
n1
## [1] 308

Length of summer (n2):

n2 <- length(Summer$Enterococci..cfu.100ml.)
n2
## [1] 308

sdp2:

sdp2 = ((n1 - 1) * sd1^2 + (n2 - 1) * sd2^2)/(n1 + n2 - 2)
sdp2
## [1] 79011.16

Standard error:

se = sqrt(sdp2 * (1/n1 + 1/n2))
se
## [1] 22.65082

TestStat:

TestStat = (m1 - m2 - 0)/se
TestStat
## [1] -0.5627503

PValue:

Pvalue = pt(abs(TestStat), n1 + n2 - 2, lower.tail = F)
Pvalue
## [1] 0.2869052
sdiff = Winter$Enterococci..cfu.100ml. - Summer$Enterococci..cfu.100ml.

qqnorm(sdiff)
qqline(sdiff)

Shapiro-Wilk normality test:

shapiro.test(sdiff)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  sdiff
## W = 0.18393, p-value < 2.2e-16

Q-Q plot line does not show a reasonable straight line because there are many outliers, hence normality assumption may not be met. Shapiro Wilk test gives an extremely small value, which means that the data does not follow a normal distribution.

Therefore, Z test and T test results should be taken with caution.

2.3.1.1 Hypothesis Testing

Hypothesis H0 : There is no difference: m1=m2 H1 : There is a difference: m1<m2

Assumption

Test-statistic = observed test statistic is -0.5627503 P-value = 0.2869052

2.3.2 Conclusion

To test the hypothesis that there was a relationship between the seasons and the cfu levels in the different beaches, we ran a Test statistic, observing a value of -0.5627503, and a P-value of 0.2869052. We therefore found there was no strong relationship between the seasons temperatures and the cfu levels in the different beaches. The sea temperature of sydney beaches varies between 18oC at the lowest in winter, and 24oC at the highest in summer. (Weather in sydney, 2019) We found that the rate of reproduction of the bacteria remains roughly constant over that temperature range, therefore the results obtained were in line with expected results from our research. Boehm and Sassoubre, 2014 We found that in summer, we had many outliers in the cfu levels of different beaches on different days. This higher number of outliers could be explained by the increase in rainfall in summer. According to our research, rainfall leads to higher cfu levels in the beaches due to the release of sewage.
